{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"180a73af-1c38-4af1-bae8-d615d54e6365","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2**, which supports constructor injection for `TestContext`. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IAsyncInitialization, IAsyncCleanup\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n\n    // Constructor injection for TestContext (MSTest 3.8+)\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // Synchronous init here (lightweight setup only)\n    }\n\n    // Async initialization — runs after constructor, before each test\n    public Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        // await async setup (e.g., DB connections, HTTP clients)\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    // Async cleanup — runs after each test\n    public Task CleanupAsync()\n    {\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_testContext);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **Constructor injection** for `TestContext` replaces the old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property pattern.\n- **`IAsyncInitialization`** — implement for async per-test setup (runs after constructor).\n- **`IAsyncCleanup`** — implement for async per-test teardown.\n- Keep the constructor lightweight; put expensive/async work in `InitializeAsync`.\n- `[ClassInitialize]`/`[ClassCleanup]` still work for one-time class-level setup if needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1e89a97c-a079-45fc-bb82-a1ae1b04515d","outputTokens":383,"requestId":"5812:28CF3A:3733E83:3AE8C23:6A0338AB"},"id":"fdb6b101-6c1a-43eb-9740-c74c5ee3e99f","timestamp":"2026-05-12T14:27:05.116Z","parentId":"5d3d093d-d57a-4e4f-8324-40fe1eaba21c"}
